<!--Seihaku Festival--><!--Seihaku Festival--><!--Seihaku Festival--><!--Seihaku Festival--><!--Seihaku Festival--><!--Seihaku Festival--><!--Seihaku Festival--><!--Seihaku Festival--><!--Seihaku Festival--><!--Seihaku Festival-->

{{Event information
| Event name = Seihakusai
| image = File:Dekayama.JPG
| image description = One of the largest ''dekayama'' (float) from the Seihakusai Festival
| Type = {{ill|Festival|ja|祭り|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Festival|qq=}}
| Date = May
| Venue = {{ill|Ōjinushi Shrine|ja|大地主神社|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ōjinushi Shrine|qq=}}, {{ill|Nanao|ja|七尾市|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Nanao|qq=}}, {{ill|Ishikawa Prefecture|ja|石川県|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ishikawa Prefecture|qq=}}
}}
[[File:Nanao May 5 2006 crowds.jpg|thumb|Crowds at Seihakusai on May 5, 2006]]
'''Seihakusai''' (青柏祭) is the annual {{ill|Reitaisai|ja|例大祭|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Reitaisai|qq=}} of {{ill|Ōjinushi Shrine|ja|大地主神社|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ōjinushi Shrine|qq=}}, held every year in {{ill|Nanao|ja|七尾市|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Nanao|qq=}}, {{ill|Ishikawa Prefecture|ja|石川県|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ishikawa Prefecture|qq=}}, from {{ill|May 1|ja|5月1日|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/May 1|qq=}} to {{ill|May 5|ja|5月5日|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/May 5|qq=}}. It is one of the {{ill|Four Major Festivals of Nanao|ja|七尾四大祭|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Four Major Festivals of Nanao|qq=}} along with the {{ill|Okuma Kabuto Festival|ja|お熊甲祭|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Okuma Kabuto Festival|qq=}}, {{ill|Mukōda Fire Festival|ja|向田の火祭り|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Mukōda Fire Festival|qq=}}, and {{ill|Ishizaki Hōtō Festival|ja|石崎奉燈祭|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ishizaki Hōtō Festival|qq=}}.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.city.nanao.lg.jp/kikaku-s/shise/sesaku/1sogokekaku/honpen/documents/kihonkeikaku_1_4_5.pdf|title=Basic Plan: Chapter 1, Arts and Culture|access-date=2024-08-04|publisher=Nanao City|page=88}}</ref>{{Refnest|group="Note"|The Ishizaki Hōtō Festival, {{ill|Nanao Gion Festival|ja|七尾祇園祭|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Nanao Gion Festival|qq=}}, and {{ill|Nanao Port Festival|ja|七尾港まつり|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Nanao Port Festival|qq=}} are sometimes also included in the four major festivals.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://yamaguchi-ev.com/ishikawa-event/1692/|title=Events in Ishikawa Prefecture in May|access-date=2024-08-04|publisher=Yamaguchi Corporation}}</ref>}}

The festival is designated as a [[Nationally Designated Important Intangible Folk Cultural Property]], and its ''dekayama'' floats are also registered as part of the {{ill|UNESCO Intangible Cultural Heritage|ja|無形文化遺産|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/UNESCO Intangible Cultural Heritage|qq=}}.

== Overview ==

The name "Seihakusai" comes from the tradition of offering {{ill|Shinsen|ja|神饌|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shinsen|qq=}} on fresh oak leaves (''seihaku''). Each of the three mountain towns (''yamachō'')—{{ill|Fuchū-chō|ja|府中町|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Fuchū-chō|qq=}}, {{ill|Kaji-chō|ja|鍛冶町|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kaji-chō|qq=}}, and {{ill|Uomachi|ja|魚町|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Uomachi|qq=}}—contributes one enormous float known as a ''dekayama.'' The name "dekayama" originates from the local word ''dekai'' (big) to describe the enormous size of the floats.<ref>[http://www.nanao-cci.or.jp/dekayama/event.html History of Seihakusai Dekayama Preservation Society]</ref>

During the festival, these colossal floats are pulled through the narrow streets of Nanao, barely clearing eaves and utility poles, with spectacular corner-turning performances. Visitors are welcome to help pull the floats during straight-line segments or turns. 

== History ==

The festival is said to have originated in {{ill|981 AD|ja|天元4th year|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/981 AD|qq=}}, when {{ill|Minamoto no Shitagō|ja|源順|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Minamoto no Shitagō|qq=}}, the governor of {{ill|Noto Province|ja|能登国|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Noto Province|qq=}}, designated it as the provincial festival. The current floats are believed to date back to the late {{ill|Muromachi period|ja|室町時代|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Muromachi period|qq=}}, under the rule of {{ill|Hatakeyama Yoshitō|ja|畠山義統|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Hatakeyama Yoshitō|qq=}}, though the exact origins remain unclear.<ref>[http://www7.ocn.ne.jp/~kita3079/seihakusai-dekayama-hozonkai-21.htm Nanao City Seihakusai Float Procession]</ref>

== Dekayama Floats ==

Each ''dekayama'' measures approximately 12 meters in height, 13 meters in length, and weighs around 20 tons, making them among the largest in Japan. Built without nails, the floats rely on traditional binding techniques using藤づる (wisteria vines). Each float is elaborately decorated with kabuki-themed dioramas, featuring hand-crafted figurines dressed in detailed costumes.

== Facilities Showcasing Seihakusai ==

* {{ill|Wakura Onsen Omatsuri Hall|ja|和倉温泉お祭り会館|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Wakura Onsen Omatsuri Hall|qq=}} – A cultural center in {{ill|Wakura|ja|和倉町|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Wakura|qq=}}, Nanao, dedicated to Nanao’s four major festivals, including Seihakusai, showcasing a full-scale replica of a ''dekayama.''
* {{ill|Noto Food Festival Market|ja|能登食祭市場|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Noto Food Festival Market|qq=}} – Features a display of a historic ''dekayama'' wheel at its entrance.

