The festival is said to have originated in {{ill|981 AD|ja|天元4th year|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/981 AD|qq=}}, when {{ill|Minamoto no Shitagō|ja|源順|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Minamoto no Shitagō|qq=}}, the governor of {{ill|Noto Province|ja|能登国|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Noto Province|qq=}}, designated it as the provincial festival. The current floats are believed to date back to the late {{ill|Muromachi period|ja|室町時代|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Muromachi period|qq=}}, under the rule of {{ill|Hatakeyama Yoshitō|ja|畠山義統|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Hatakeyama Yoshitō|qq=}}, though the exact origins remain unclear.<ref>[http://www7.ocn.ne.jp/~kita3079/seihakusai-dekayama-hozonkai-21.htm Nanao City Seihakusai Float Procession]</ref>

== Dekayama Floats ==

Each ''dekayama'' measures approximately 12 meters in height, 13 meters in length, and weighs around 20 tons, making them among the largest in Japan. Built without nails, the floats rely on traditional binding techniques using藤づる (wisteria vines). Each float is elaborately decorated with kabuki-themed dioramas, featuring hand-crafted figurines dressed in detailed costumes.

== Facilities Showcasing Seihakusai ==

* {{ill|Wakura Onsen Omatsuri Hall|ja|和倉温泉お祭り会館|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Wakura Onsen Omatsuri Hall|qq=}} – A cultural center in {{ill|Wakura|ja|和倉町|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Wakura|qq=}}, Nanao, dedicated to Nanao’s four major festivals, including Seihakusai, showcasing a full-scale replica of a ''dekayama.''
* {{ill|Noto Food Festival Market|ja|能登食祭市場|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Noto Food Festival Market|qq=}} – Features a display of a historic ''dekayama'' wheel at its entrance.

